 #block-yui_3_17_2_1_1773167649516_8044 { } KNOW BEFORE YOU GO! Getting Her
 e Since parking is extremely limited—and we’re obviously keen on green
  —we strongly recommend walking\, biking or public transportation.&nbsp\
 ; 👟 By Foot : The park entrance is at the intersection of Copeland and 
 East D Streets\, in central Petaluma.&nbsp\; 🚲 By Bike: Pedal over and 
 lock up at the racks in front of the park entrance. 🚎 By Public Transpo
 rtation: The park is a short\, ¼-mile walk from:&nbsp\; Petaluma SMART Tr
 ain station at 200 Lakeville Street&nbsp\; Petaluma Transit Routes 10 or 1
 1—Copeland Street stop&nbsp\; And LumaGo will take you right to the park
 ! What to Bring Your wallet—for lots of yummy items and beautiful handma
 de goods! A partner\, a friend\, your grandmother\, your kids! Did we ment
 ion the FREE portraits?&nbsp\; Sunscreen\, hats\, water\, picnic blankets\
 , and comfortable shoes. (Mud alert if it rained the day before.) Fido! Do
 gs are always welcome\, as long as pup stays on leash. A Few More Details 
 Paths and parking will be very limited access while we’re setting up tha
 t morning. We love birds at the park\, but please no early birds to the ev
 ent. There are two accessible portable restrooms—one near the central ga
 thering area and one near the David Yearsley River Heritage Center. The pe
 rimeter trail is off-road wheelchair and stroller accessible. It’s looki
 ng like a sunny day—note that shade is limited. #block-yui_3_17_2_1_1773
